WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:10.000
The COVID Symptom Study was a project that used an app that was developed by the health data science company ZOE in the UK,

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.000
and it was launched in the UK together with King's College London.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:21.000
The app was also launched subsequently in the US with the help of Harvard University,

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.000
and in Sweden with us from Lund University and our friends from Uppsala University.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
This app was launched very early in the pandemic in Europe and in the US,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:39.000
so early March for the UK and the US, but also in April for Sweden.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:45.000
During the time of the project, that lasts more or less two to three years,

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:54.000
we had engaged 4.7 million participants from these countries that contributed with over 500 million data reports.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.000
In Sweden, the COVID Symptom Study Sweden was a collaborative effort.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:06.000
We had engaged researchers, but also data scientists, medical doctors, and of course the public.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
It was in its core a public health intervention.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:19.000
We want to understand a little bit more about this disease in terms of which groups were at risk,

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:26.000
but also which symptoms were associated to a COVID positive test.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Of course, we were trying to map the spread of COVID since it was a public health intervention,

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:43.000
so we want to give the public information about the prevalence of that COVID infection in their region in Sweden.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:45.000
So how did it work?

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.000
The participants would download our app in their phones,

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:59.000
and the first day that they downloaded, they would give us information about their baseline, their demographic.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:08.000
For instance, they would give us their age, but also if they want to inform gender,

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:17.000
but also information about the postal code that we later on used to group them in regional groups

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:21.000
to understand the spread of the virus as a map.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:32.000
From that day on, the participants would be reminded to report once a day at least about how they were feeling that day,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
if they were feeling healthy or if they were feeling unhealthy.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
If the participants said that they were not feeling healthy,

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:44.000
then we would ask them with a list of symptoms to point us which symptoms they were having

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:49.000
or to write in a text field which symptoms that they were having.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:57.000
We also asked participants that at the time had availability of COVID tests,

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:01.000
since as I said, this was very early in the pandemic,

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
COVID tests were not available for everyone.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Most groups that were at risk that we identified in the beginning,

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:16.000
but also health workers were able to have these tests.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:21.000
So we asked for anyone in our app that had information about tests in terms of,

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
did you take a test? What was the result of the test?

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
To also report that, and this will be important. I'll show you how.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:34.000
So, gladly, we had engagement of all over Sweden.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:40.000
And as I said, we collect information about their demographic, their health history,

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:43.000
their symptoms and their COVID tests.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:49.000
And with the baseline, we could create the groups that I mentioned

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:54.000
and understand that these participants were coming from all around Sweden,

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:00.000
but mainly from the biggest metropolitan regions.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:08.000
So Malmö, Lund, Skåne, Gothenburg and Västra Gotland and Stockholm and Uppsala in Stockholm.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:16.000
And we also found that most of our participants were female from the age 50 to 59 years old.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:23.000
The interesting thing that we used in this app, as I said,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:30.000
was the symptom survey and the COVID test survey, right?

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.000
So very early on, we had a large engagement of people, as I said.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:41.000
So we had over 140,000 people participating in Sweden,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:47.000
which is a big number for Sweden, given that Sweden has 11 million people.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:54.000
So from these 140,000 people, we had 20,000 people more or less

00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:00.000
that had access for at least one COVID test and that had reported that to us.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:06.000
And with this information, we were able to plot to try to understand

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:16.000
the differences between the syndromic presentation of a positive COVID

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:21.000
and the presentation of a negative COVID, as you can see here.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:27.000
And we see right away that there is a difference in shape of these curves, right?

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:33.000
So this is a COVID positive, and we see that the symptoms are peaking higher

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:41.000
and that they have a longer wide area under the curve, right?

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:47.000
While the negative COVID are peaking and they go down really quickly.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And just for your reference, on the x-axis here, we have the days of the test standardized.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:03.000
So day zero is the day of the participant that they received the result of the test.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:07.000
And then we have 50 days before and 50 days after that, right?

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.000
So we standardized them to try to understand how are the presentation,

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.000
the prevalence of these symptoms.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:20.000
And here we have the symptom that peak the highest is loss of smell in a positive COVID.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:26.000
And today we know that loss of smell in the first two waves were rightly associated with COVID.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
But you have to remember that at the time we had,

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:34.000
we didn't know much about which symptoms were more characteristic of COVID.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:43.000
In fact, we were the first to study to identify loss of smell as a symptom

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:48.000
that was highly associated with COVID at this stage.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:53.000
Of course, like during the time, this changed a bit.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:59.000
So then this difference in the curves gave us a hint that we could use this data

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:09.000
that could be valuable to create a model so we could predict COVID based on the symptoms only.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:11.000
So that's exactly what we did.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:16.000
We use a very simple model, a logistic regression with a loss of penalty model

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:19.000
in these 20,000 participants.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:26.000
And we identified them, the symptoms and interactions of symptoms that were associated

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:34.000
positively and negatively with a true COVID result test, right?

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:41.000
So as I said, loss of smell was the symptom that had the highest association to a positive COVID,

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
the highest weight for a positive COVID, right?

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.000
But we had other symptoms such as fever, unusual muscle pain, and it goes on.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:58.000
And we had also some negative associations such as abdominal pain was not a COVID symptom

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:02.000
at the time, at least not positively associated, right?

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:13.000
So then with this information, we then started predicting COVID based on the symptoms

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.000
that our participants were reporting daily.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:24.000
So basically we were taking these 20,000 population, created a model, and then used the model

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:31.000
to predict COVID in the part of the population that didn't have access to the test.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:38.000
And then we start right away plotting the daily prevalence of COVID at the national level,

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.000
as you can see the right, but also at regional level.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.000
As I said, we were grouping them by the postal code.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:52.000
Everything here was, you have some GIFs here, but everything here was published in a shiny app

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:56.000
that I will show you soon.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:05.000
We then use other data information from other sources to try to understand if our model

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.000
was actually telling us the truth, right?

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:09.000
Some validation.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:17.000
So here on your left, you see our predictions with the confidence intervals in red, right?

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:23.000
And here in black, you see COVID-19 hospitalizations in the country.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:30.000
And as you can see, we are very good at predicting the first wave and the second wave.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:37.000
But we have some artifact here around September that year, in 2020, that we predict a high COVID,

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:44.000
not as high as the first and second wave, but a peak on COVID, and that was not the true

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:50.000
based on the COVID-19 hospitalizations in the country, right?

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:59.000
So then we understand that probably our model was suffering for either change of something,

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
the real scenario of the world at that point, right?

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
In Sweden, in the case.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:15.000
So what we did was we updated our model with time dependency in terms of we were concerned

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:20.000
that people that were downloading the app were downloading the app because they were feeling ill,

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.000
so they would download the app and then stop using the app.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:31.000
So we use a time dependency, just excluding part of the population that were downloading the app

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:37.000
and reporting right away, but adding a weight to that time that they were reporting.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:45.000
So with that, we were actually able to go over and to create a better model.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:52.000
And this I just want to show you as an example as things are multiple and as models,

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:58.000
but also other things like we later on had to use different models because we were having

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.000
different types of COVID over the time.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:06.000
So I just would like to use this as an example of how we need to adapt in the real world

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:16.000
with machine learning models so we can create a correction prediction of the COVID or anything, right?

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:24.000
The whole process of creating the model was very iteratively,

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:31.000
and it's better described in a paper that we published in Nature Communications in 2022.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.000
I will soon show you the name of the paper.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:41.000
But one more thing that I would like to show to you is that we used that model together

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:48.000
with the hospitalization data to try to predict hospitalization seven days before it happened.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:56.000
And our model performed really well, as you can see in the median absolute percentage errors

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
for the regions that you can see here.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:03.000
So Stockholm, Västergötland, Skåne, these are all regions of Sweden, right?

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:10.000
So these were the five regions that our model performed the best in terms of predicting

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:17.000
a hospitalization that would happen in the future using our model together with other data

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:24.000
that were also available in the country at that time.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:30.000
So as I said, everything is very well described in our publication Nature Communications.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
So this is the publication.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:38.000
But if you want to know more about the very nitty gritty details about the project,

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:48.000
you can also find my PhD thesis in which I detail much more about the creation of the COVID Symptom Study Sweden,

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.000
but as well as the creation of these two tools here.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:13:04.000
The COVID Symptom Study Sweden dashboard, that was a shiny dashboard, and the COVID Symptom Package.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.000
There you will find more details about that.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:16.000
But very quickly, the package was a need that we felt that there was a lot of people that want to use our data,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
our predictions for modeling in specific regions.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:26.000
So we then made these aggregated data available for data scientists and researchers in Sweden.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:40.000
Yeah, so the data collection of the study ends in July 2022, but the project continues.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:48.000
We have projects related to vaccination, but also related to groups at risk and long COVID as well.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:14:01.000
But I just want to show this study example as how we can use these survey data and apps like that

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:08.000
to create some valuable information to real-time tracking of diseases.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:19.000
And as many epidemiologists have been saying lately, we might be having also future pandemics very soon.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:25.000
And this type of study with the use of R, with the use of data science tools,

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:36.000
we can quickly use these tools to create a project and deliver some very insightful information

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:42.000
for public health makers, but also for researchers at a very fast time.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.000
Thank you very much. I will open for questions.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:52.000
If you want to reach me out, you can find me on LinkedIn or you can email me. Thank you.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:01.000
Okay, you can hear us.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:02.000
Yes.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:03.000
Excellent.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:05.000
Yay!

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
We enjoyed the talk.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
There's a few questions in slide O.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:14.000
Yeah.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:15.000
We have a few minutes.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:21.000
Could you please explain more about how the time-dependent model was different from your original main model?

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:23.000
So, sure.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:28.000
Really quickly, because throughout the whole study, we had different models.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:38.000
So, the first model was only taking into consideration the symptoms, the presentation, basically,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:45.000
and how they present at any time given a period that we had set in the beginning,

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:51.000
given a period like seven days before and seven days after the date of the test.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:16:00.000
What we did in the time-dependent model was to add a weight of time to the day of the report.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:12.000
So, closer to the dates of the test, then the symptoms had a bigger weight.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:21.000
But also, another thing, very quickly, is that we started excluding participants that downloaded the data,

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:29.000
the app, and they will report right away, because we were finding a huge bias with a lot of people entering this study

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
because they were feeling sick.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
But you can read more on the publications that I mentioned.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:37.000
Okay, excellent.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:43.000
Speaking of the publication, also for Hugo, the app must have been developed very quickly

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:46.000
since your first Nature paper was published in 2020.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
It was, I think, March, I thought.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.000
Can you touch on the rapid development of that app?

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:57.000
That was a very quick learning curve.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:05.000
So, basically, what happened was the ZOE team in the UK had a huge group of data scientists working for them

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:09.000
in Lund University, as usually is in public universities.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
It was me, the whole group.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
So, I had to learn Shiny very quickly.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.000
And I'm very glad for the huge Shiny community that we have online,

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.000
because at the time we didn't have also ChatGPT, right?

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:24.000
So, I had to go a lot to these resources online.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
So, it was, yeah, it was very quick.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:38.000
But we spent a few months actually just publishing ggplot maps without any interaction.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:43.000
And then it was a process that was developing day by day, you know?

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:50.000
We had a MVP, and then we just grew by then when I was learning to do different things.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
But yeah, in two months we deployed that.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:18:01.000
And I had a lot of help as well from the guys in the Shiny live.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:02.000
I forgot the name, I'm sorry.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
But the Shiny server, yeah.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
The Shiny server people helped me a lot with that.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:07.000
We had a couple of meetings.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:08.000
Excellent.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:09.000
Okay, thanks.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:10.000
That's all we have time for.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
Let's give Yugo another round of applause.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:14.000
Thank you.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:15.000
Thank you very much.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.000
Thank you.

